            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How the PA Local Income Tax (EIT) Calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Pennsylvania’s local earned income tax (EIT) is imposed by
                municipalities and school districts on wages, salaries, and net
                profits. Under Act 32, employers withhold local tax based on
                your resident rate and, in some cases, the non‑resident rate
                where you work.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator lets you enter your own resident and work EIT
                rates and then applies the Act 32 allocation rules to estimate:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Your effective combined local EIT rate</li>
                <li>Annual and per‑pay local tax withheld</li>
                <li>
                  How much goes to your resident municipality, resident school
                  district, and work municipality
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Core formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Annualize income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If you enter income per pay period, the calculator converts it
                  to annual income:
                </p>
                <ul>
                  <li>Annual = Weekly × 52</li>
                  <li>Annual = Biweekly × 26</li>
                  <li>Annual = Monthly × 12</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Convert rates to decimals</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \( r_\text{res} = \frac{\text{resident municipal} +
                  \text{resident school}}{100} \)
                  <br />
                  \( r_\text{work} = \frac{\text{work non‑resident}}{100} \)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Step 3 – Apply Act 32 allocation</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Total EIT rate used:
                  <br />
                  \( r_\text{total} = \max(r_\text{res}, r_\text{work}) \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Annual local EIT:
                  <br />
                  \( \text{Tax}_\text{annual} = \text{Income}_\text{annual}
                  \times r_\text{total} \)
                </p>
                <p>Allocation (simplified Act 32 logic):</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Work municipality gets up to \( r_\text{work} \times
                    \text{Income}_\text{annual} \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Resident municipality + school district get the remainder,
                    up to \( r_\text{res} \times \text{Income}_\text{annual} \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>
                Example: Live in a 1.5% area, work in a 1% non‑resident area
              </h3>
              <p>
                Suppose you earn $60,000 per year, live in a municipality +
                school district with a combined EIT rate of 1.5%, and work in a
                municipality with a 1.0% non‑resident rate.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Resident total rate = 1.5%</li>
                <li>Work non‑resident rate = 1.0%</li>
                <li>Effective rate = max(1.5%, 1.0%) = 1.5%</li>
                <li>Annual local EIT = $60,000 × 1.5% = $900</li>
                <li>Work municipality receives $60,000 × 1.0% = $600</li>
                <li>
                  Resident municipality + school district receive the remaining
                  $300
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>What counts as earned income for PA local tax?</h2>
              <p>Local EIT generally applies to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Wages, salaries, tips, and bonuses</li>
                <li>Commissions and certain incentive pay</li>
                <li>Net profits from self‑employment or a business</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Local EIT does <strong>not</strong> apply to:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Interest and dividends</li>
                <li>Social Security benefits</li>
                <li>Pensions and IRA distributions</li>
                <li>Unemployment compensation</li>
                <li>Most capital gains</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Local Services Tax (LST) is a separate flat tax (often up to $52
                per year) and is <strong>not</strong> included in this
                calculator.
              </p>

              <h2>Resident vs. non‑resident rates and PSD codes</h2>
              <p>
                Each PA municipality and school district has a Political
                Subdivision (PSD) code and associated resident and non‑resident
                EIT rates. Employers use your residency certification form
                (often a DCED form) to determine which rates to withhold.
              </p>
              <p>To find your official rates, you can use:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The DCED local tax information portal and PSD code search
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your local tax collector’s website (e.g., Keystone,
                  Berkheimer, Jordan Tax Service)
                </li>
                <li>Your municipality or school district tax office</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Once you know your resident and non‑resident rates, enter them
                into this calculator for a more accurate estimate.
              </p>

              <h2>Special note about Philadelphia</h2>
              <p>
                Philadelphia imposes a separate Wage Tax instead of the standard
                Act 32 EIT structure. If you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Live in Philadelphia and work in Philadelphia, you generally
                  pay only the Wage Tax.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Live outside Philadelphia and work in the city, your employer
                  withholds the Wage Tax, and some or all of it may be credited
                  against your resident EIT.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator does <strong>not</strong> compute the
                Philadelphia Wage Tax itself, but you can still:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Estimate your resident EIT if you live outside Philadelphia,
                  and
                </li>
                <li>
                  Approximate how much of your Wage Tax might be credited, by
                  entering the Wage Tax rate as the “work non‑resident rate.”
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an educational estimator, not an official DCED or
                  local tax collector tool.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It assumes your entire income is subject to EIT and does not
                  handle partial‑year residency, multiple jobs, or detailed
                  credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Actual withholding and liability can differ based on local
                  ordinances, credits, and your full tax situation.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always confirm your final liability and filing requirements with
                your local tax collector, the Pennsylvania Department of
                Community and Economic Development (DCED), or a qualified tax
                professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about PA local income tax</h2>

              <h3>Do I have to file a local earned income tax return?</h3>
              <p>
                In most Pennsylvania jurisdictions, residents must file an
                annual local earned income tax return, even if all tax was
                withheld by an employer. Your local tax collector (e.g.,
                Keystone, Berkheimer, Jordan Tax Service, or a county tax
                bureau) provides the forms and e‑file options.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my employer did not withhold local EIT?</h3>
              <p>
                If your employer did not withhold local EIT, you are usually
                still responsible for paying it directly to your local tax
                collector. Many collectors require quarterly estimated payments
                if you expect to owe above a certain threshold.
              </p>

              <h3>How does local EIT interact with PA state income tax?</h3>
              <p>
                PA state income tax (3.07%) is separate from local EIT. Local
                EIT is in addition to state tax and is administered by local
                collectors. This calculator only estimates the local portion,
                not your state income tax.
              </p>

              <h3>Can local EIT be withheld from non‑resident workers?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If you work in a PA municipality that levies a non‑resident
                EIT, your employer may withhold that tax even if you live
                outside the municipality. Under Act 32, that non‑resident tax is
                credited against your resident EIT, up to your resident rate.
              </p>
